# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-rds
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Amazon RDS was first released on 26 October 2009, supporting MySQL databases.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] This was followed by support for Oracle Database in June 2011, Microsoft SQL Server in May 2012, PostgreSQL in November 2013, and MariaDB (a fork of MySQL) in October 2015, and an additional 80 features during 2017.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] In November 2014 AWS announced Amazon Aurora, a MySQL-compatible database offering enhanced high availability and performance, and in October 2017 a PostgreSQL-compatible database offering was launched.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] In March 2019 AWS announced support of PostgreSQL 11 in RDS, five months after official release.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] New database instances can be launched from the AWS Management Console or using the Amazon RDS APIs.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Amazon RDS offers different features to support different use cases.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] In May 2010 Amazon announced Multi-Availability Zone deployment support.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Amazon RDS Multi-Availability Zone (AZ) allows users to automatically provision and maintain a synchronous physical or logical "standby" replica, depending on database engine, in a different Availability Zone (independent infrastructure in a physically separate location).
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Multi-AZ database instance can be developed at creation time or modified to run as a Multi-AZ deployment later.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Multi-AZ deployments aim to provide enhanced availability and data durability for MySQL, MariaDB, Oracle, PostgreSQL and SQL Server instances and are targeted for production environments.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] In the event of planned database maintenance or unplanned service disruption, Amazon RDS automatically fails over to the up-to-date standby, allowing database operations to resume without administrative intervention.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Multi-AZ RDS instances are optional and have a cost associated with them.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] When creating a RDS instance, the user is asked if they would like to use a Multi-AZ RDS instance.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] In Multi-AZ RDS deployments backups are done in the standby instance so I/O activity is not suspended any time but users may experience elevated latencies for a few minutes during backups.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Read replicas allow different use cases such as to scale in for read-heavy database workloads.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] There are up to five replicas available for MySQL, MariaDB, and PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Instances use the native, asynchronous replication functionality of their respective database engines.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] They have no backups configured by default and are accessible and can be used for read scaling.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] MySQL and MariaDB read replicas can be made writeable again since October 2012; PostgreSQL read replicas do not support it.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Replicas are done at database instance level and do not support replication at database or table level.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Performance metrics for Amazon RDS are available from the AWS Management Console or the Amazon CloudWatch API.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] In December 2015, Amazon announced an optional enhanced monitoring feature that provides an expanded set of metrics for the MySQL, MariaDB, and Aurora database engines.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Amazon RDS instances are priced very similarly to Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2).
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] RDS is charged per hour and comes in two packages: On-Demand DB Instances and Reserved DB Instances.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] On-Demand Instances are at an ongoing hourly usage rate.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Reserved RDS Instances are offered in 1-year and 3-year terms and include no-upfront, partial-upfront, and all-upfront payment options.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Currently, AWS does not offer a 3-year reservation with an "no-upfront" payment option.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Apart from the hourly cost of running the RDS instance, users are charged for the amount of storage provisioned, data transfers and input and output operations performed.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] AWS have introduced Provisioned Input and Output Operations, in which the user can define how many IO per second are required by their application.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] IOPS can contribute significantly to the total cost of running the RDS instance.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Amazon RDS also has an Aurora Serverless option.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] The serverless pricing unit is dollars per ACU hour.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] This option is designed for customers that need to dramatically scale workloads.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] As part of the AWS Free Tier, the Amazon RDS Free Tier helps new AWS customers get started with a managed database service in the cloud for free.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] You can use the Amazon RDS Free Tier to develop new applications, test existing applications, or simply gain hands-on experience with Amazon RDS.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Amazon RDS creates and saves automated backups of RDS DB instances.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] The first snapshot of a DB instance contains the data for the full DB instance and subsequent snapshots are incremental, maximum retention period is 35 days.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] In Multi-AZ RDS deployments backups are done in the standby instance so I/O activity is not suspended for any amount of time but you may experience elevated latencies for a few minutes during backups.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Database instances can be managed from the AWS Management Console, using the Amazon RDS APIs and using AWS CLI.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Since 1 June 2017, you can stop AWS RDS instances from AWS Management Console or AWS CLI for 7 days at a time.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] After 7 days, it will be automatically started, and since September 2018 RDS instances can be protected from accidental deletion.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Increase DB space is supported, but not decrease allocated space.
[src:aws-rds/amazon-relational-database-service] Additionally there is at least a six-hour period where new allocation cannot be done.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In computing, a **database** is an organized collection of data or a type of data store based on the use of a **database management system** (**DBMS**), the software that interacts with end users, applications, and the database itself to capture and analyze the data.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The DBMS additionally encompasses the core facilities provided to administer the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The sum total of the database, the DBMS and the associated applications can be referred to as a **database system**.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Often the term "database" is also used loosely to refer to any of the DBMS, the database system or an application associated with the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Professional book indexers used index cards in the creation of book indexes until they were replaced by indexing software in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Small databases can be stored on a file system, while large databases are hosted on computer clusters or cloud storage.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The design of databases spans formal techniques and practical considerations, including data modeling, efficient data representation and storage, query languages, security and privacy of sensitive data, and distributed computing issues, including supporting concurrent access and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Computer scientists may classify database management systems according to the database models that they support.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Relational databases became dominant in the 1980s.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] These model data as rows and columns in a series of tables, and the vast majority use SQL for writing and querying data.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In the 2000s, non-relational databases became popular, collectively referred to as NoSQL, because they use different query languages.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The DBMS provides various functions that allow entry, storage and retrieval of large quantities of information and provides ways to manage how that information is organized.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Because of the close relationship between them, the term "database" is often used casually to refer to both a database and the DBMS used to manipulate it.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Outside the world of professional information technology, the term *database* is often used to refer to any collection of related data (such as a spreadsheet or a card index) as size and usage requirements typically necessitate use of a database management system.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Both a database and its DBMS conform to the principles of a particular database model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] "Database system" refers collectively to the database model, database management system, and database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Physically, database servers are dedicated computers that hold the actual databases and run only the DBMS and related software.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database servers are usually multiprocessor computers, with generous memory and RAID disk arrays used for stable storage.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Hardware database accelerators, connected to one or more servers via a high-speed channel, are also used in large-volume transaction processing environments.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] DBMSs are found at the heart of most database applications.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] DBMSs may be built around a custom multitasking kernel with built-in networking support, but modern DBMSs typically rely on a standard operating system to provide these functions.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Since DBMSs comprise a significant market, computer and storage vendors often take into account DBMS requirements in their own development plans.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The sizes, capabilities, and performance of databases and their respective DBMSs have grown in orders of magnitude.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] These performance increases were enabled by the technology progress in the areas of processors, computer memory, computer storage, and computer networks.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The concept of a database was made possible by the emergence of direct access storage media such as magnetic disks, which became widely available in the mid-1960s; earlier systems relied on sequential storage of data on magnetic tape.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The subsequent development of database technology can be divided into three eras based on data model or structure: navigational, SQL/relational, and post-relational.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The two main early navigational data models were the hierarchical model and the CODASYL model (network model).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] These were characterized by the use of pointers (often physical disk addresses) to follow relationships from one record to another.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The relational model, first proposed in 1970 by Edgar F.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Codd, departed from this tradition by insisting that applications should search for data by content, rather than by following links.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The relational model employs sets of ledger-style tables, each used for a different type of entity.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Only in the mid-1980s did computing hardware become powerful enough to allow the wide deployment of relational systems (DBMSs plus applications).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] By the early 1990s, however, relational systems dominated in all large-scale data processing applications, and as of 2018 they remain dominant: IBM Db2, Oracle, MySQL, and Microsoft SQL Server are the most searched DBMS.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The dominant database language, standardized SQL for the relational model, has influenced database languages for other data models.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Object databases were developed in the 1980s to overcome the inconvenience of object–relational impedance mismatch, which led to the coining of the term "post-relational" and also the development of hybrid object–relational databases.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The next generation of post-relational databases in the late 2000s became known as NoSQL databases, introducing fast key–value stores and document-oriented databases.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A competing "next generation" known as NewSQL databases attempted new implementations that retained the relational/SQL model while aiming to match the high performance of NoSQL compared to commercially available relational DBMSs.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The introduction of the term *database* coincided with the availability of direct-access storage (disks and drums) from the mid-1960s onwards.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The term represented a contrast with the tape-based systems of the past, allowing shared interactive use rather than daily batch processing.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The Oxford English Dictionary cites a 1962 report by the System Development Corporation of California as the first to use the term "data-base" in a specific technical sense.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] As computers grew in speed and capability, a number of general-purpose database systems emerged; by the mid-1960s a number of such systems had come into commercial use.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Interest in a standard began to grow, and Charles Bachman, author of one such product, the Integrated Data Store (IDS), founded the Database Task Group within CODASYL, the group responsible for the creation and standardization of COBOL.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In 1971, the Database Task Group delivered their standard, which generally became known as the *CODASYL approach*, and soon a number of commercial products based on this approach entered the market.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The CODASYL approach offered applications the ability to navigate around a linked data set which was formed into a large network.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Later systems added B-trees to provide alternate access paths.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Many CODASYL databases also added a declarative query language for end users (as distinct from the navigational API).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] However, CODASYL databases were complex and required significant training and effort to produce useful applications.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] IBM also had its own DBMS in 1966, known as Information Management System (IMS).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] IMS was a development of software written for the Apollo program on the System/360.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] IMS was generally similar in concept to CODASYL, but used a strict hierarchy for its model of data navigation instead of CODASYL's network model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Both concepts later became known as navigational databases due to the way data was accessed: the term was popularized by Bachman's 1973 Turing Award presentation *The Programmer as Navigator*.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] IMS is classified by IBM as a hierarchical database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] IDMS and Cincom Systems' TOTAL databases are classified as network databases.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Codd worked at IBM in San Jose, California, in an office primarily involved in the development of hard disk systems.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] He was unhappy with the navigational model of the CODASYL approach, notably the lack of a "search" facility.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In 1970, he wrote a number of papers that outlined a new approach to database construction that eventually culminated in the groundbreaking *A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks*.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The paper described a new system for storing and working with large databases.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Instead of records being stored in some sort of linked list of free-form records as in CODASYL, Codd's idea was to organize the data as a number of "tables", each table being used for a different type of entity.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Each table would contain a fixed number of columns containing the attributes of the entity.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Splitting the data into a set of normalized tables (or *relations*) aimed to ensure that each "fact" was only stored once, thus simplifying update operations.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Virtual tables called *views* could present the data in different ways for different users, but views could not be directly updated.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Codd used mathematical terms to define the model: relations, tuples, and domains rather than tables, rows, and columns.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The terminology that is now familiar came from early implementations.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Codd would later criticize the tendency for practical implementations to depart from the mathematical foundations on which the model was based.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The use of primary keys (user-oriented identifiers) to represent cross-table relationships, rather than disk addresses, had two primary motivations.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] From an engineering perspective, it enabled tables to be relocated and resized without expensive database reorganization.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] There is no loss of expressiveness compared with the hierarchic or network models, though the connections between tables are no longer so explicit.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In the hierarchic and network models, records were allowed to have a complex internal structure.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] For example, the salary history of an employee might be represented as a "repeating group" within the employee record.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In the relational model, the process of normalization led to such internal structures being replaced by data held in multiple tables, connected only by logical keys.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] For instance, a common use of a database system is to track information about users, their name, login information, various addresses and phone numbers.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In the navigational approach, all of this data would be placed in a single variable-length record.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In the relational approach, the data would be *normalized* into a user table, an address table and a phone number table (for instance).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Records would be created in these optional tables only if the address or phone numbers were actually provided.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] As well as identifying rows/records using logical identifiers rather than disk addresses, Codd changed the way in which applications assembled data from multiple records.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Rather than requiring applications to gather data one record at a time by navigating the links, they would use a declarative query language that expressed what data was required, rather than the access path by which it should be found.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Finding an efficient access path to the data became the responsibility of the database management system, rather than the application programmer.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This process, called query optimization, depended on the fact that queries were expressed in terms of mathematical logic.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Beginning in 1973, INGRES delivered its first test products which were generally ready for widespread use in 1979.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] INGRES was similar to System R in a number of ways, including the use of a "language" for data access, known as QUEL.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Over time, INGRES moved to the emerging SQL standard.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] IBM itself did one test implementation of the relational model, PRTV, and a production one, Business System 12, both now discontinued.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Honeywell wrote MRDS for Multics, and now there are two new implementations: Alphora Dataphor and Rel.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Most other DBMS implementations usually called *relational* are actually SQL DBMSs.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In 1970, the University of Michigan began development of the MICRO Information Management System based on D.L.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The university in 1974 hosted a debate between Codd and Bachman which Bruce Lindsay of IBM later described as "throwing lightning bolts at each other!".
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] MICRO was used to manage very large data sets by the US Department of Labor, the U.S.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Environmental Protection Agency, and researchers from the University of Alberta, the University of Michigan, and Wayne State University.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] It ran on IBM mainframe computers using the Michigan Terminal System.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The system remained in production until 1998.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, attempts were made to build database systems with integrated hardware and software.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The underlying philosophy was that such integration would provide higher performance at a lower cost.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Examples were IBM System/38, the early offering of Teradata, and the Britton Lee, Inc. database machine.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Another approach to hardware support for database management was ICL's CAFS accelerator, a hardware disk controller with programmable search capabilities.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In the long term, these efforts were generally unsuccessful because specialized database machines could not keep pace with the rapid development and progress of general-purpose computers.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Thus most database systems nowadays are software systems running on general-purpose hardware, using general-purpose computer data storage.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] However, this idea is still pursued in certain applications by some companies like Netezza and Oracle (Exadata).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] IBM formed a team led by Codd that started working on a prototype system, *System R* despite opposition from others at the company.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The first version was ready in 1974/5, and work then started on multi-table systems in which the data could be split so that all of the data for a record (some of which is optional) did not have to be stored in a single large "chunk".
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Subsequent multi-user versions were tested by customers in 1978 and 1979, by which time a standardized query language – SQL – had been added.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Codd's ideas were establishing themselves as both workable and superior to CODASYL, pushing IBM to develop a true production version of System R, known as *SQL/DS*, and, later, *Database 2* (IBM Db2).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Larry Ellison's Oracle Database (or more simply, Oracle) started from a different chain, based on IBM's papers on System R.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Though Oracle V1 implementations were completed in 1978, it was not until Oracle Version 2 when Ellison beat IBM to market in 1979.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Stonebraker went on to apply the lessons from INGRES to develop a new database, Postgres, which is now known as PostgreSQL.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] PostgreSQL is often used for global mission-critical applications (the .org and .info domain name registries use it as their primary data store, as do many large companies and financial institutions).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In Sweden, Codd's paper was also read and Mimer SQL was developed in the mid-1970s at Uppsala University.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In 1984, this project was consolidated into an independent enterprise.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Another data model, the entity–relationship model, emerged in 1976 and gained popularity for database design as it emphasized a more familiar description than the earlier relational model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Later on, entity–relationship constructs were retrofitted as a data modeling construct for the relational model, and the difference between the two has become irrelevant.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Besides IBM and various software companies such as Sybase and Informix Corporation, most large computer hardware vendors by the 1980s had their own database systems such as DEC's VAX Rdb/VMS.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The decade ushered in the age of desktop computing.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The new computers empowered their users with spreadsheets like Lotus 1-2-3 and database software like dBASE.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The dBASE product was lightweight and easy for any computer user to understand out of the box.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Wayne Ratliff, the creator of dBASE, stated: "dBASE was different from programs like BASIC, C, FORTRAN, and COBOL in that a lot of the dirty work had already been done.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] By the start of the decade databases had become a billion-dollar industry in about ten years.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The 1990s, along with a rise in object-oriented programming, saw a growth in how data in various databases were handled.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Programmers and designers began to treat the data in their databases as objects.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] That is to say that if a person's data were in a database, that person's attributes, such as their address, phone number, and age, were now considered to belong to that person instead of being extraneous data.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This allows for relations between data to be related to objects and their attributes and not to individual fields.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The term "object–relational impedance mismatch" described the inconvenience of translating between programmed objects and database tables.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Object databases and object–relational databases attempt to solve this problem by providing an object-oriented language (sometimes as extensions to SQL) that programmers can use as alternative to purely relational SQL.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] On the programming side, libraries known as object–relational mappings (ORMs) attempt to solve the same problem.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database sales grew rapidly during the dotcom bubble and, after its end, the rise of ecommerce.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The popularity of open source databases such as MySQL has grown since 2000, to the extent that Ken Jacobs of Oracle said in 2005 that perhaps "these guys are doing to us what we did to IBM".
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] XML databases are a type of structured document-oriented database that allows querying based on XML document attributes.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] XML databases are mostly used in applications where the data is conveniently viewed as a collection of documents, with a structure that can vary from the very flexible to the highly rigid: examples include scientific articles, patents, tax filings, and personnel records.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] NoSQL databases are often very fast, do not require fixed table schemas, avoid join operations by storing denormalized data, and are designed to scale horizontally.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Some NoSQL databases, including graph databases such as Neo4j, represent data as nodes and edges to model relationships between entities.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In recent years, there has been a strong demand for massively distributed databases with high partition tolerance, but according to the CAP theorem, it is impossible for a distributed system to simultaneously provide consistency, availability, and partition tolerance guarantees.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A distributed system can satisfy any two of these guarantees at the same time, but not all three.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] For that reason, many NoSQL databases are using what is called eventual consistency to provide both availability and partition tolerance guarantees with a reduced level of data consistency.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] NewSQL is a class of modern relational databases that aims to provide the same scalable performance of NoSQL systems for online transaction processing (read-write) workloads while still using SQL and maintaining the ACID guarantees of a traditional database system.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Databases are used to support internal operations of organizations and to underpin online interactions with customers and suppliers (see Enterprise software).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Databases are used to hold administrative information and more specialized data, such as engineering data or economic models.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Examples include computerized library systems, flight reservation systems, computerized parts inventory systems, and many content management systems that store websites as collections of webpages in a database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] One way to classify databases involves the type of their contents, for example: bibliographic, document-text, statistical, or multimedia objects.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Another way is by their application area, for example: accounting, music compositions, movies, banking, manufacturing, or insurance.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A third way is by some technical aspect, such as the database structure or interface type.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This section lists a few of the adjectives used to characterize different kinds of databases.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database." Examples of DBMS's include MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle Database, and Microsoft Access.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The DBMS acronym is sometimes extended to indicate the underlying database model, with RDBMS for the relational, OODBMS for the object (oriented) and ORDBMS for the object–relational model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Other extensions can indicate some other characteristics, such as DDBMS for a distributed database management systems.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The functionality provided by a DBMS can vary enormously.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The core functionality is the storage, retrieval and update of data.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] It is also generally to be expected the DBMS will provide a set of utilities for such purposes as may be necessary to administer the database effectively, including import, export, monitoring, defragmentation and analysis utilities.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The core part of the DBMS interacting between the database and the application interface sometimes referred to as the database engine.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Often DBMSs will have configuration parameters that can be statically and dynamically tuned, for example the maximum amount of main memory on a server the database can use.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The trend is to minimize the amount of manual configuration, and for cases such as embedded databases the need to target zero-administration is paramount.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The large major enterprise DBMSs have tended to increase in size and functionality and have involved up to thousands of human years of development effort throughout their lifetime.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Early multi-user DBMS typically only allowed for the application to reside on the same computer with access via terminals or terminal emulation software.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The client–server architecture was a development where the application resided on a client desktop and the database on a server allowing the processing to be distributed.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This evolved into a multitier architecture incorporating application servers and web servers with the end user interface via a web browser with the database only directly connected to the adjacent tier.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A general-purpose DBMS will provide public application programming interfaces (API) and optionally a processor for database languages such as SQL to allow applications to be written to interact with and manipulate the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A special purpose DBMS may use a private API and be specifically customized and linked to a single application.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] For example, an email system performs many of the functions of a general-purpose DBMS such as message insertion, message deletion, attachment handling, blocklist lookup, associating messages an email address and so forth however these functions are limited to what is required to handle email.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] External interaction with the database will be via an application program that interfaces with the DBMS.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This can range from a database tool that allows users to execute SQL queries textually or graphically, to a website that happens to use a database to store and search information.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A programmer will code interactions to the database (sometimes referred to as a datasource) via an application program interface (API) or via a database language.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The particular API or language chosen will need to be supported by DBMS, possibly indirectly via a preprocessor or a bridging API.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Some API's aim to be database independent, ODBC being a commonly known example.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Other common API's include JDBC and ADO.NET.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database languages are specific to a particular data model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database storage is the container of the physical materialization of a database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] It comprises the *internal* (physical) *level* in the database architecture.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] It also contains all the information needed (e.g., metadata, "data about the data", and internal data structures) to reconstruct the *conceptual level* and *external level* from the internal level when needed.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Databases as digital objects contain three layers of information which must be stored: the data, the structure, and the semantics.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Proper storage of all three layers is needed for future preservation and longevity of the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Putting data into permanent storage is generally the responsibility of the database engine a.k.a.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A DBMS, while in operation, always has its database residing in several types of storage (e.g., memory and external storage).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The database data and the additional needed information, possibly in very large amounts, are coded into bits.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Some DBMSs support specifying which character encoding was used to store data, so multiple encodings can be used in the same database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Various low-level database storage structures are used by the storage engine to serialize the data model so it can be written to the medium of choice.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Techniques such as indexing may be used to improve performance.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Conventional storage is row-oriented, but there are also column-oriented and correlation databases.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Often storage redundancy is employed to increase performance.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A common example is storing *materialized views*, which consist of frequently needed *external views* or query results.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Storing such views saves the expensive computing them each time they are needed.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The downsides of materialized views are the overhead incurred when updating them to keep them synchronized with their original updated database data, and the cost of storage redundancy.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Updates of a replicated object need to be synchronized across the object copies.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In many cases, the entire database is replicated.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database security deals with all various aspects of protecting the database content, its owners, and its users.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] It ranges from protection from intentional unauthorized database uses to unintentional database accesses by unauthorized entities (e.g., a person or a computer program).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database access control deals with controlling who (a person or a certain computer program) are allowed to access what information in the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database access controls are set by special authorized (by the database owner) personnel that uses dedicated protected security DBMS interfaces.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This may be managed directly on an individual basis, or by the assignment of individuals and privileges to groups, or (in the most elaborate models) through the assignment of individuals and groups to roles which are then granted entitlements.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Data security prevents unauthorized users from viewing or updating the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Using passwords, users are allowed access to the entire database or subsets of it called "subschemas".
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] For example, an employee database can contain all the data about an individual employee, but one group of users may be authorized to view only payroll data, while others are allowed access to only work history and medical data.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] If the DBMS provides a way to interactively enter and update the database, as well as interrogate it, this capability allows for managing personal databases.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Change and access logging records who accessed which attributes, what was changed, and when it was changed.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Logging services allow for a forensic database audit later by keeping a record of access occurrences and changes.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Sometimes application-level code is used to record changes rather than leaving this in the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Monitoring can be set up to attempt to detect security breaches.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Therefore, organizations must take database security seriously because of the many benefits it provides.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Organizations will be safeguarded from security breaches and hacking activities like firewall intrusion, virus spread, and ransom ware.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This helps in protecting the company's essential information, which cannot be shared with outsiders at any cause.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Database transactions can be used to introduce some level of fault tolerance and data integrity after recovery from a crash.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A database transaction is a unit of work, typically encapsulating a number of operations over a database (e.g., reading a database object, writing, acquiring or releasing a lock, etc.), an abstraction supported in database and also other systems.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Each transaction has well defined boundaries in terms of which program/code executions are included in that transaction (determined by the transaction's programmer via special transaction commands).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The acronym ACID describes some ideal properties of a database transaction: atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A database built with one DBMS is not portable to another DBMS (i.e., the other DBMS cannot run it).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] However, in some situations, it is desirable to migrate a database from one DBMS to another.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The reasons are primarily economical (different DBMSs may have different total costs of ownership or TCOs), functional, and operational (different DBMSs may have different capabilities).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The migration involves the database's transformation from one DBMS type to another.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] The transformation should maintain (if possible) the database related application (i.e., all related application programs) intact.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Thus, the database's conceptual and external architectural levels should be maintained in the transformation.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] It may be desired that also some aspects of the architecture internal level are maintained.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A complex or large database migration may be a complicated and costly (one-time) project by itself, which should be factored into the decision to migrate.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] This is in spite of the fact that tools may exist to help migration between specific DBMSs.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Typically, a DBMS vendor provides tools to help import databases from other popular DBMSs.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] After designing a database for an application, the next stage is building the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Typically, an appropriate general-purpose DBMS can be selected to be used for this purpose.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] A DBMS provides the needed user interfaces to be used by database administrators to define the needed application's data structures within the DBMS's respective data model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Other user interfaces are used to select needed DBMS parameters (like security related, storage allocation parameters, etc.).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] In some cases, the database becomes operational while empty of application data, and data are accumulated during its operation.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] After the database is created, initialized and populated it needs to be maintained.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Various database parameters may need changing and the database may need to be tuned (tuning) for better performance; application's data structures may be changed or added, new related application programs may be written to add to the application's functionality, etc.
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] Sometimes it is desired to bring a database back to a previous state (for many reasons, e.g., cases when the database is found corrupted due to a software error, or if it has been updated with erroneous data).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] To achieve this, a backup operation is done occasionally or continuously, where each desired database state (i.e., the values of its data and their embedding in database's data structures) is kept within dedicated backup files (many techniques exist to do this effectively).
[src:aws-rds/database-p01] When it is decided by a database administrator to bring the database back to this state (e.g., by specifying this state by a desired point in time when the database was in this state), these files are used to restore that state.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Static analysis techniques for software verification can be applied also in the scenario of query languages.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] In particular, the *Abstract interpretation framework has been extended to the field of query languages for relational databases as a way to support sound approximation techniques.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The semantics of query languages can be tuned according to suitable abstractions of the concrete domain of data.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The abstraction of relational database systems has many interesting applications, in particular, for security purposes, such as fine-grained access control, watermarking, etc.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Increasingly, there are calls for a single system that incorporates all of these core functionalities into the same build, test, and deployment framework for database management and source control.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Borrowing from other developments in the software industry, some market such offerings as "DevOps for database".
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The first task of a database designer is to produce a conceptual data model that reflects the structure of the information to be held in the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] A common approach to this is to develop an entity–relationship model, often with the aid of drawing tools.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Another popular approach is the Unified Modeling Language.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] A successful data model will accurately reflect the possible state of the external world being modeled: for example, if people can have more than one phone number, it will allow this information to be captured.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The answers to these questions establish definitions of the terminology used for entities (customers, products, flights, flight segments) and their relationships and attributes.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Producing the conceptual data model sometimes involves input from business processes, or the analysis of workflow in the organization.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] This can help to establish what information is needed in the database, and what can be left out.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] For example, it can help when deciding whether the database needs to hold historic data as well as current data.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Having produced a conceptual data model that users are happy with, the next stage is to translate this into a schema that implements the relevant data structures within the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] This process is often called logical database design, and the output is a logical data model expressed in the form of a schema.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Whereas the conceptual data model is (in theory at least) independent of the choice of database technology, the logical data model will be expressed in terms of a particular database model supported by the chosen DBMS.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] (The terms *data model* and *database model* are often used interchangeably, but in this article we use *data model* for the design of a specific database, and *database model* for the modeling notation used to express that design).
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The most popular database model for general-purpose databases is the relational model, or more precisely, the relational model as represented by the SQL language.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The process of creating a logical database design using this model uses a methodical approach known as normalization.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The goal of normalization is to ensure that each elementary "fact" is only recorded in one place, so that insertions, updates, and deletions automatically maintain consistency.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The final stage of database design is to make the decisions that affect performance, scalability, recovery, security, and the like, which depend on the particular DBMS.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] This is often called *physical database design*, and the output is the physical data model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] A key goal during this stage is data independence, meaning that the decisions made for performance optimization purposes should be invisible to end-users and applications.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] There are two types of data independence: Physical data independence and logical data independence.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Physical design is driven mainly by performance requirements, and requires a good knowledge of the expected workload and access patterns, and a deep understanding of the features offered by the chosen DBMS.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Another aspect of physical database design is security.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] It involves both defining access control to database objects as well as defining security levels and methods for the data itself.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] A database model is a type of data model that determines the logical structure of a database and fundamentally determines in which manner data can be stored, organized, and manipulated.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The most popular example of a database model is the relational model (or the SQL approximation of relational), which uses a table-based format.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] An object–relational database combines the two related structures.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] While there is typically only one conceptual and internal view of the data, there can be any number of different external views.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] This allows users to see database information in a more business-related way rather than from a technical, processing viewpoint.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] For example, a financial department of a company needs the payment details of all employees as part of the company's expenses, but does not need details about employees that are in the interest of the human resources department.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Thus different departments need different *views* of the company's database.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The three-level database architecture relates to the concept of *data independence* which was one of the major initial driving forces of the relational model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The idea is that changes made at a certain level do not affect the view at a higher level.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] For example, changes in the internal level do not affect application programs written using conceptual level interfaces, which reduces the impact of making physical changes to improve performance.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The conceptual view provides a level of indirection between internal and external.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] On the one hand it provides a common view of the database, independent of different external view structures, and on the other hand it abstracts away details of how the data are stored or managed (internal level).
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] In principle every level, and even every external view, can be presented by a different data model.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] In practice usually a given DBMS uses the same data model for both the external and the conceptual levels (e.g., relational model).
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The internal level, which is hidden inside the DBMS and depends on its implementation, requires a different level of detail and uses its own types of data structure types.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Database technology has been an active research topic since the 1960s, both in academia and in the research and development groups of companies (for example IBM Research).
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Research activity includes theory and development of prototypes.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] Notable research topics have included models, the atomic transaction concept, related concurrency control techniques, query languages and query optimization methods, RAID, and more.
[src:aws-rds/database-p02] The database research area has several dedicated academic journals (for example, *ACM Transactions on Database Systems*-TODS, *Data and Knowledge Engineering*-DKE) and annual conferences (e.g., ACM SIGMOD, ACM PODS, VLDB, IEEE ICDE).
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A **database transaction** symbolizes a unit of work, performed within a database management system (or similar system) against a database, that is treated in a coherent and reliable way independent of other transactions.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A transaction generally represents any change in a database.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] To provide isolation between programs accessing a database concurrently.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] If this isolation is not provided, the programs' outcomes are possibly erroneous.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] In a database management system, a transaction is a single unit of logic or work, sometimes made up of multiple operations.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Any logical calculation done in a consistent mode in a database is known as a transaction.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] One example is a transfer from one bank account to another: the complete transaction requires subtracting the amount to be transferred from one account and adding that same amount to the other.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Database practitioners often refer to these properties of database transactions using the acronym ACID.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Databases and other data stores which treat the integrity of data as paramount often include the ability to handle transactions to maintain the integrity of data.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A single transaction consists of one or more independent units of work, each reading and/or writing information to a database or other data store.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] When this happens it is often important to ensure that all such processing leaves the database or data store in a consistent state.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Examples from double-entry accounting systems often illustrate the concept of transactions.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] In double-entry accounting every debit requires the recording of an associated credit.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A transactional system would make both entries pass or both entries would fail.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] By treating the recording of multiple entries as an atomic transactional unit of work the system maintains the integrity of the data recorded.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] In other words, nobody ends up with a situation in which a debit is recorded but no associated credit is recorded, or vice versa.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A **transactional database** is a DBMS that provides the ACID properties for a bracketed set of database operations (begin-commit).
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Transactions ensure that the database is always in a consistent state, even in the event of concurrent updates and failures.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] All the write operations within a transaction have an all-or-nothing effect, that is, either the transaction succeeds and all writes take effect, or otherwise, the database is brought to a state that does not include any of the writes of the transaction.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Transactions also ensure that the effect of concurrent transactions satisfies certain guarantees, known as isolation level.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] The highest isolation level is serializability, which guarantees that the effect of concurrent transactions is equivalent to their serial (i.e. sequential) execution.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Most modern relational database management systems support transactions.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] NoSQL databases prioritize scalability along with supporting transactions in order to guarantee data consistency in the event of concurrent updates and accesses.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] In a database system, a transaction might consist of one or more data-manipulation statements and queries, each reading and/or writing information in the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Users of database systems consider consistency and integrity of data as highly important.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Execute a set of data manipulations and/or queries.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] If no error occurs, then commit the transaction.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] If an error occurs, then roll back the transaction.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A transaction commit operation persists all the results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A transaction rollback operation does not persist the partial results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] In no case can a partial transaction be committed to the database since that would leave the database in an inconsistent state.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Internally, multi-user databases store and process transactions, often by using a transaction ID or XID.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] There are multiple varying ways for transactions to be implemented other than the simple way documented above.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Nested transactions, for example, are transactions which contain statements within them that start new transactions (i.e. sub-transactions).
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] *Multi-level transactions* are a variant of nested transactions where the sub-transactions take place at different levels of a layered system architecture (e.g., with one operation at the database-engine level, one operation at the operating-system level).
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Another type of transaction is the compensating transaction.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Transactions are available in most SQL database implementations, though with varying levels of robustness.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] For example, MySQL began supporting transactions from early version 3.23, but the InnoDB storage engine was not default before version 5.5.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] The earlier available storage engine, MyISAM does not support transactions.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A transaction is typically started using the command `BEGIN` (although the SQL standard specifies `START TRANSACTION`).
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] When the system processes a `COMMIT` statement, the transaction ends with successful completion.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A `ROLLBACK` statement can also end the transaction, undoing any work performed since `BEGIN`.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] If autocommit was disabled with the start of a transaction, autocommit will also be re-enabled with the end of the transaction.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] One can set the isolation level for individual transactional operations as well as globally.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] At the highest level (`READ COMMITTED`), the result of any operation performed after a transaction has started will remain invisible to other database users until the transaction has ended.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] At the lowest level (`READ UNCOMMITTED`), which may occasionally be used to ensure high concurrency, such changes will be immediately visible.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Relational databases are traditionally composed of tables with fixed-size fields and records.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Object databases comprise variable-sized blobs, possibly serializable or incorporating a mime-type.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] The fundamental similarities between Relational and Object databases are the start and the commit or rollback.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] After starting a transaction, database records or objects are locked, either read-only or read-write.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Once the transaction is fully defined, changes are committed or rolled back atomically, such that at the end of the transaction there is no inconsistency.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Database systems implement distributed transactions as transactions accessing data over multiple nodes.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] A distributed transaction enforces the ACID properties over multiple nodes, and might include systems such as databases, storage managers, file systems, messaging systems, and other data managers.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] In a distributed transaction there is typically an entity coordinating all the process to ensure that all parts of the transaction are applied to all relevant systems.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] Moreover, the integration of Storage as a Service (StaaS) within these environments is crucial, as it offers a virtually infinite pool of storage resources, accommodating a range of cloud-based data store classes with varying availability, scalability, and ACID properties.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] This integration is essential for achieving higher availability, lower response time, and cost efficiency in data-intensive applications deployed across cloud-based data stores.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] The Namesys Reiser4 filesystem for Linux supports transactions, and as of Microsoft Windows Vista, the Microsoft NTFS filesystem supports distributed transactions across networks.
[src:aws-rds/database-transaction] There is occurring research into more data coherent filesystems, such as the Warp Transactional Filesystem (WTF).
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] A managed IT services provider is a third-party service provider that proactively monitors & manages a customer's server/network/system infrastructure, cybersecurity and end-user systems against a clearly defined Service Level Agreement (SLA).
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] Small and medium-sized businesses (SMBs), nonprofits and government agencies hire MSPs to perform a defined set of day-to-day management services so they can focus on their core businesses with reduced risk of extended system downtime or service interruptions.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] These services may include network and infrastructure management, security and monitoring.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] Most MSPs bill an upfront setup or transition fee and an ongoing flat or near-fixed monthly fee, which benefits clients by providing them with predictable IT support costs.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] Sometimes MSPs act as facilitators who manage and procure staffing services on behalf of the client.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] In such context, they may use a vendor management system (VMS) for transparency and efficiency.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] A managed service provider may also help a business create IT disaster recovery plans.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] The evolution of MSP started in the 1990s with the emergence of application service providers (ASPs) who helped pave the way for remote support for IT infrastructure.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] From the initial focus of remote monitoring and management of servers and networks, the scope of an MSP's services expanded to include mobile device management, managed security, remote firewall administration and security-as-a-service, and managed print services.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] The first books on the topic of managed services - *Service Agreements for SMB Consultants: A Quick-Start Guide to Managed Services* and *The Guide to a Successful Managed Services Practice* - were published in 2006 by Palachuk and Simpson, respectively.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] Since then, the managed services business model has gained ground among enterprise-level companies.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] As the value-added reseller (VAR) community evolved to a higher level of services, it adapted the managed service model and tailored it to SMB companies.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] As the IT infrastructure components of many SMB and large corporations are migrating to the cloud, with MSPs (managed services providers) increasingly facing the challenge of cloud computing, a number of MSPs are providing in-house cloud services or acting as brokers with cloud services providers.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] A recent survey claims that a lack of knowledge and expertise in cloud computing rather than client's reluctance, appears to be the main obstacle to this transition.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] The most common managed services revolve around IT: connectivity and bandwidth, network monitoring, security, virtualization, and disaster recovery.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] Attackers have compromised MSPs and software used by MSPs as a form of supply chain attack.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] National Cybersecurity and Communications Integration Center (NCCIC) warned the public that it knew of attackers, including advanced persistent threats, attempting to infiltrate the networks of MSPs as a way to conduct cyber espionage and intellectual property theft.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] NCCIC said that this type of attack, which dated to at least 2016, targeted MSPs because compromising them could allow attackers to access customer networks.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] By 2019, attackers began targeting MSPs to spread ransomware because hacking into a MSP could allow them to install ransomware in many MSP client systems.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] Attackers found and exploited vulnerabilities in software used by MSPs, such as remote monitoring and management products.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] In the July 2021 Kaseya VSA ransomware attack, the REvil criminal organization exploited a vulnerability in Kaseya software to attack its MSP customers with ransomware and up 1,500 companies that were clients of the MSPs.
[src:aws-rds/managed-services] In 2025, the DragonForce ransomware group attacked a MSP and used its remote monitoring and management platform to steal client data and encrypt client systems.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:aws-rds/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:aws-rds/replication-computing] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
